1
00:00:00,300 --> 00:00:02,350
- This video is sponsored by Brilliant.

2
00:00:02,649 --> 00:00:03,709
Each morning when I wake up,

3
00:00:03,710 --> 00:00:06,730
I start my day by getting three simple things;

4
00:00:06,730 --> 00:00:09,440
movement, water and sunlight.

5
00:00:09,439 --> 00:00:11,149
And together these three tiny habits

6
00:00:11,150 --> 00:00:13,270
quickly get me past that initial groggy stage

7
00:00:13,269 --> 00:00:15,178
and help me feel fully awake.

8
00:00:15,179 --> 00:00:18,699
But why are these three habits so effective in particular?

9
00:00:18,699 --> 00:00:21,399
And how do you get yourself out of bed in the first place

10
00:00:21,399 --> 00:00:22,949
so you can actually get them.

11
00:00:22,949 --> 00:00:24,338
That's what we're gonna talk about in this video

12
00:00:24,339 --> 00:00:26,848
but before we get into that, I wanna lay some groundwork.

13
00:00:26,850 --> 00:00:27,810
First and foremost

14
00:00:27,809 --> 00:00:30,228
you do not have to wake up early in the morning

15
00:00:30,230 --> 00:00:31,500
to be a productive person.

16
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:33,300
There are certainly gonna be other people here on YouTube

17
00:00:33,299 --> 00:00:34,559
we'll try to tell you differently

18
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:37,339
but the fact of the matter is different people operate

19
00:00:37,340 --> 00:00:38,569
on different schedules.

20
00:00:38,570 --> 00:00:40,130
For example, over on Brain Pickings,

21
00:00:40,130 --> 00:00:41,759
there's this fantastic infographic

22
00:00:41,759 --> 00:00:42,789
that I found a few years ago

23
00:00:42,789 --> 00:00:44,649
which compares the different wake-up times

24
00:00:44,649 --> 00:00:46,649
of some famous authors throughout history.

25
00:00:46,649 --> 00:00:48,449
And while it's true that some of them do wake up

26
00:00:48,450 --> 00:00:51,200
at obscenely early times, like Haruki Murakami,

27
00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:53,420
who gets up at 4:00 AM, when he's writing a novel.

28
00:00:53,420 --> 00:00:56,529
Others who are just as if not more successful

29
00:00:56,530 --> 00:00:58,949
and famous and productive get up at later times,

30
00:00:58,950 --> 00:01:01,019
for example C.S. Lewis and Ray Bradbury

31
00:01:01,020 --> 00:01:03,080
both got up at around 9:00 AM in the morning

32
00:01:03,079 --> 00:01:04,488
and they did just fine.

33
00:01:04,489 --> 00:01:06,172
So while some YouTubers are gonna tell you

34
00:01:06,173 --> 00:01:09,010
that you absolutely have to be getting up super early

35
00:01:09,010 --> 00:01:09,970
to be successful

36
00:01:09,969 --> 00:01:12,578
while they filmed themselves out for 4:00 AM run,

37
00:01:12,579 --> 00:01:14,849
the truth of the matter is that it's possible

38
00:01:14,849 --> 00:01:17,469
to live a perfectly productive life as a night owl.

39
00:01:17,469 --> 00:01:20,259
However, I personally have found that when I carve out time

40
00:01:20,260 --> 00:01:22,740
in the morning and actually go through a morning routine

41
00:01:22,739 --> 00:01:24,289
I tend to be more productive.

42
00:01:24,290 --> 00:01:25,640
Again, this is a personal thing,

43
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:27,309
but I've found through experimentation

44
00:01:27,310 --> 00:01:28,640
and personal experience

45
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:31,620
that I tend to use the morning hours more productively

46
00:01:31,620 --> 00:01:33,470
than I do my evening hours.

47
00:01:33,469 --> 00:01:36,018
So if I wake up earlier than I naturally would

48
00:01:36,019 --> 00:01:37,539
and I carve out time in the morning

49
00:01:37,540 --> 00:01:40,740
I tend to waste less time and get more out of my day.

50
00:01:40,739 --> 00:01:42,729
And you might be in the exact same boat.

51
00:01:42,730 --> 00:01:45,460
You might find that your mornings are just more productive,

52
00:01:45,459 --> 00:01:47,209
you have more energy, you have more drive

53
00:01:47,209 --> 00:01:48,418
if you wake up early.

54
00:01:48,420 --> 00:01:49,629
But if that's you,

55
00:01:49,629 --> 00:01:52,289
you probably have also faced the same problem that I faced

56
00:01:52,290 --> 00:01:54,319
which is that when you wake up in the morning

57
00:01:54,319 --> 00:01:55,968
you feel like a truck hit you,

58
00:01:55,969 --> 00:01:58,388
you feel lethargic, you feel groggy, you feel tired.

59
00:01:58,390 --> 00:02:01,050
The only thing you wanna do is hit the snooze button.

60
00:02:01,049 --> 00:02:03,616
So number one how can you avoid that snooze button

61
00:02:03,617 --> 00:02:04,850
and number two,

62
00:02:04,849 --> 00:02:06,429
how can you get past that tired feeling

63
00:02:06,430 --> 00:02:07,690
as quickly as possible?

64
00:02:07,689 --> 00:02:09,499
Let's focusing on that sequence of three habits

65
00:02:09,500 --> 00:02:12,589
I talked about in the intro, water, sunlight and movement.

66
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:13,930
Through personal experimentation

67
00:02:13,930 --> 00:02:15,329
as well as some scientific research

68
00:02:15,330 --> 00:02:17,300
I have found that this sequence of habits

69
00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:19,460
is possibly the most important thing

70
00:02:19,460 --> 00:02:22,200
to getting your body woken up and feeling energetic.

71
00:02:22,199 --> 00:02:23,929
Besides of course, getting enough sleep.

72
00:02:23,930 --> 00:02:24,930
So let's start with movement.

73
00:02:24,930 --> 00:02:26,450
How much movement,

74
00:02:26,449 --> 00:02:27,959
what kind of movement do you need

75
00:02:27,960 --> 00:02:29,820
to get your body feeling awake?

76
00:02:29,819 --> 00:02:30,968
When I first started discovering

77
00:02:30,969 --> 00:02:32,929
the power of movement to wake my body up

78
00:02:32,930 --> 00:02:33,790
when I was in college

79
00:02:33,789 --> 00:02:34,622
and I decided to sign up

80
00:02:34,622 --> 00:02:37,609
for a 6:00 AM, ROTC military fitness class.

81
00:02:37,610 --> 00:02:39,920
The school was offering this to both military kids,

82
00:02:39,919 --> 00:02:41,118
but also to civilians

83
00:02:41,120 --> 00:02:42,400
and I was in the latter category,

84
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:44,250
and to get to that class,

85
00:02:44,250 --> 00:02:46,649
I actually had to wake up at about 5:30 in the morning

86
00:02:46,650 --> 00:02:49,029
so I could get across campus and be there on time.

87
00:02:49,030 --> 00:02:50,699
And I'm an early bird,

88
00:02:50,699 --> 00:02:52,179
I do like getting up early in the morning

89
00:02:52,180 --> 00:02:54,939
but 5:30 is a little bit early even for me.

90
00:02:54,939 --> 00:02:57,148
So every time my alarm would go off

91
00:02:57,150 --> 00:02:59,799
I would hate it and I would really wanna go back to sleep.

92
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:02,070
But I learned something interesting

93
00:03:02,069 --> 00:03:04,098
because I had to get out of bed,

94
00:03:04,099 --> 00:03:05,758
I had to be to class on time,

95
00:03:05,759 --> 00:03:07,299
I never once hit the snooze button

96
00:03:07,300 --> 00:03:10,380
and most importantly, I was immediately moving

97
00:03:10,379 --> 00:03:11,619
after the alarm went off.

98
00:03:11,620 --> 00:03:13,529
And because I was getting that initial movement

99
00:03:13,530 --> 00:03:15,439
right after waking up, getting out of bed,

100
00:03:15,439 --> 00:03:17,088
getting dressed, running out the door

101
00:03:17,090 --> 00:03:19,340
that lethargic feeling that I had

102
00:03:19,340 --> 00:03:21,960
immediately after waking up didn't last very long.

103
00:03:21,960 --> 00:03:22,793
And I learned that as long

104
00:03:22,793 --> 00:03:24,990
as I was getting enough sleep over the longterm

105
00:03:24,990 --> 00:03:27,452
that energy lasted me pretty much the entire day.

106
00:03:27,451 --> 00:03:29,599
But you don't have to go

107
00:03:29,599 --> 00:03:31,008
to an ROTC fitness class

108
00:03:31,009 --> 00:03:32,749
or do an hour and a half of exercise

109
00:03:32,750 --> 00:03:33,949
to feel awake in the morning.

110
00:03:33,949 --> 00:03:36,609
Because the main thing I observed is just getting myself

111
00:03:36,610 --> 00:03:37,443
out of bed,

112
00:03:37,443 --> 00:03:40,439
having that sort of Damocles hanging over my head

113
00:03:40,439 --> 00:03:43,289
the deadline got me past that lethargic feeling

114
00:03:43,289 --> 00:03:44,869
before I even left my dorm.

115
00:03:44,870 --> 00:03:47,689
So getting some initial movement even just a little bit

116
00:03:47,689 --> 00:03:49,279
in the morning can really go a long way

117
00:03:49,280 --> 00:03:50,870
to helping you feel more awake

118
00:03:50,870 --> 00:03:53,959
especially if you also add water and sunlight.

119
00:03:53,960 --> 00:03:55,510
Let's talk about sunlight for a second.

120
00:03:55,509 --> 00:03:58,529
Sunlight in particular affects your body's circadian rhythm

121
00:03:58,530 --> 00:04:00,100
which is this internal clock

122
00:04:00,099 --> 00:04:01,328
this process that governs

123
00:04:01,330 --> 00:04:03,370
when you feel sleepy, when you fall asleep

124
00:04:03,370 --> 00:04:04,890
and when you wake up.

125
00:04:04,889 --> 00:04:07,299
When sunlight hits the photo receptors in your eyes,

126
00:04:07,300 --> 00:04:08,990
they actually send signals to your brain

127
00:04:08,990 --> 00:04:11,349
telling you that, "Hey, it's time to wake up."

128
00:04:11,349 --> 00:04:13,498
And that's not all research has also found

129
00:04:13,500 --> 00:04:15,060
that this morning sunlight exposure

130
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:17,129
also helps improve the overall quality

131
00:04:17,129 --> 00:04:18,489
of your sleep going forward.

132
00:04:18,490 --> 00:04:21,070
A 2017 study found that exposure in the morning

133
00:04:21,069 --> 00:04:23,658
to what they called circadian-effective light

134
00:04:23,660 --> 00:04:26,340
was associated with both improved sleep quality

135
00:04:26,339 --> 00:04:30,478
and earlier sleep onset, AKA falling asleep faster.

136
00:04:30,480 --> 00:04:33,359
Now this term circadian-effective light

137
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:35,889
is an interesting one because it doesn't just refer

138
00:04:35,889 --> 00:04:36,799
to sunlight.

139
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:39,020
Rather it refers to some certain qualities of lights

140
00:04:39,019 --> 00:04:40,228
including its intensity,

141
00:04:40,230 --> 00:04:43,509
and how well it covers certain areas of the color spectrum.

142
00:04:43,509 --> 00:04:44,389
There are certain areas

143
00:04:44,389 --> 00:04:46,159
of the visual light spectrum that are associated

144
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:47,910
with triggering those photoreceptors

145
00:04:47,910 --> 00:04:49,860
and governing our circadian rhythm.

146
00:04:49,860 --> 00:04:51,420
And most of the lights

147
00:04:51,420 --> 00:04:54,870
in our interior environments don't cover that area

148
00:04:54,870 --> 00:04:55,870
of the color spectrum.

149
00:04:55,870 --> 00:04:57,220
There is at least one company

150
00:04:57,220 --> 00:04:58,270
working on light bulbs

151
00:04:58,269 --> 00:04:59,728
that you can actually go out and buy right now

152
00:04:59,730 --> 00:05:02,370
that do purport to cover this area of light spectrum

153
00:05:02,370 --> 00:05:03,670
and there are some early research,

154
00:05:03,670 --> 00:05:05,170
mostly in office environments

155
00:05:05,170 --> 00:05:06,950
that have some promising results.

156
00:05:06,949 --> 00:05:08,689
But before you rush out

157
00:05:08,689 --> 00:05:10,549
and go buy a $500 desk lamp

158
00:05:10,550 --> 00:05:12,420
that the purports to governor your circadian rhythm

159
00:05:12,420 --> 00:05:14,730
realized that the most effective,

160
00:05:14,730 --> 00:05:17,830
circadian-effective light is gonna be sunlight,

161
00:05:17,829 --> 00:05:18,662
which makes sense

162
00:05:18,663 --> 00:05:20,600
because these little light bulbs are just light bulbs

163
00:05:20,600 --> 00:05:22,999
and the sun is a freaking star.

164
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:24,139
Now, when it comes to water

165
00:05:24,139 --> 00:05:26,018
I haven't been able to find quite as much strong

166
00:05:26,019 --> 00:05:28,108
scientific evidence as I have for sunlight

167
00:05:28,110 --> 00:05:29,850
as to why it helps you wake up so well.

168
00:05:29,850 --> 00:05:32,220
But through personal experimentation and experience

169
00:05:32,220 --> 00:05:34,880
I have found that when I wake up and drink a glass of water

170
00:05:34,879 --> 00:05:37,629
it gets me past that groggy stage really quickly

171
00:05:37,629 --> 00:05:40,629
and it's a great way to help me feel even more awake.

172
00:05:40,629 --> 00:05:42,469
So get in a bed immediately,

173
00:05:42,470 --> 00:05:44,060
move to a different room of your house

174
00:05:44,060 --> 00:05:45,010
so you get some movement

175
00:05:45,009 --> 00:05:47,959
and ideally some sunlight and drink a glass of water.

176
00:05:47,959 --> 00:05:50,157
This doesn't involve an ROTC fitness class,

177
00:05:50,158 --> 00:05:51,999
it doesn't involve a long hike in the woods,

178
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,899
it's incredibly simple but it's effective nonetheless.

179
00:05:55,899 --> 00:05:57,959
Of course, this assumes you can get yourself

180
00:05:57,959 --> 00:05:59,489
out of bed in the first place

181
00:05:59,490 --> 00:06:01,599
and avoid the temptations of the snooze button.

182
00:06:01,600 --> 00:06:02,979
So how do you do that?

183
00:06:02,980 --> 00:06:04,270
Well for that problem

184
00:06:04,269 --> 00:06:06,898
let's think back to the ROTC fitness class.

185
00:06:06,899 --> 00:06:08,818
I talked about how when the alarm went off

186
00:06:08,819 --> 00:06:09,998
and I was taking that class

187
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:11,850
I never once hit the snooze button.

188
00:06:11,850 --> 00:06:13,850
And the reason for that should be pretty obvious.

189
00:06:13,850 --> 00:06:15,700
I had to get out of bed if I didn't,

190
00:06:15,699 --> 00:06:18,518
I was gonna be late for class and I would get a worst grade.

191
00:06:18,519 --> 00:06:21,728
So that class gave me a very strong reason

192
00:06:21,730 --> 00:06:22,680
to get out of bed.

193
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:24,630
And you probably understand the power of this

194
00:06:24,629 --> 00:06:26,899
if you've ever had to get up for an early morning flight,

195
00:06:26,899 --> 00:06:28,209
you don't wanna get up at 4:00 AM

196
00:06:28,209 --> 00:06:30,369
but the prospect of missing the flight

197
00:06:30,370 --> 00:06:32,192
gets you out of bed all the same.

198
00:06:32,192 --> 00:06:33,690
But here's the problem

199
00:06:33,689 --> 00:06:35,608
carving out time for yourself in the morning

200
00:06:35,610 --> 00:06:36,670
building a morning routine

201
00:06:36,670 --> 00:06:40,235
by definition means there's no real strong deadline

202
00:06:40,235 --> 00:06:41,739
or pressing engagement

203
00:06:41,740 --> 00:06:43,010
and you have to get out of bed for.

204
00:06:43,009 --> 00:06:44,979
So what do you do in these situations?

205
00:06:44,980 --> 00:06:46,419
Well, the words of my friend,

206
00:06:46,420 --> 00:06:48,120
Tiago Forte come to mind here

207
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:49,820
some point last year, he tweeted

208
00:06:49,819 --> 00:06:52,238
you can't compete with somebody who's having fun.

209
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:53,940
And I think the context of that tweet

210
00:06:53,939 --> 00:06:55,449
was for people who are building businesses

211
00:06:55,449 --> 00:06:56,282
or building products.

212
00:06:56,283 --> 00:06:58,359
But I think that sentiment applies

213
00:06:58,360 --> 00:07:00,239
to many of the things in our life,

214
00:07:00,240 --> 00:07:02,380
including the prospect of getting out of bed earlier

215
00:07:02,379 --> 00:07:03,598
than you normally would.

216
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:05,529
Think about it a version of yourself

217
00:07:05,529 --> 00:07:07,289
that hates getting up has nothing

218
00:07:07,290 --> 00:07:08,620
to look forward to in the morning

219
00:07:08,620 --> 00:07:11,200
is trying to entirely rely on self-discipline

220
00:07:11,199 --> 00:07:12,779
can never compete with a version of you

221
00:07:12,779 --> 00:07:14,059
that's excited to get up

222
00:07:14,060 --> 00:07:16,620
as something fun to look forward to.

223
00:07:16,620 --> 00:07:18,100
So there's the solution.

224
00:07:18,100 --> 00:07:20,090
Add something, it could be anything,

225
00:07:20,089 --> 00:07:22,479
no matter how small that you're excited for it

226
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:23,609
into your morning routine,

227
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:26,580
give yourself a reason to anticipate getting up

228
00:07:26,579 --> 00:07:27,412
in the morning

229
00:07:27,413 --> 00:07:28,260
and you're gonna find getting up

230
00:07:28,259 --> 00:07:29,989
to be so much easier.

231
00:07:29,990 --> 00:07:31,669
Self-discipline is still important to cultivate,

232
00:07:31,670 --> 00:07:34,060
yes but on the other side of the coin

233
00:07:34,060 --> 00:07:36,169
when we are doing something we enjoy

234
00:07:36,170 --> 00:07:38,041
where the resistance does not overweigh

235
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:39,759
how much we enjoy the thing

236
00:07:39,759 --> 00:07:42,518
we don't have to rely on self-discipline in the first place.

237
00:07:42,519 --> 00:07:45,048
Personally that thing for me is riding my bike to work

238
00:07:45,050 --> 00:07:46,469
and listening to an audio book.

239
00:07:46,470 --> 00:07:49,030
Recently, I got a co-working space in downtown Denver

240
00:07:49,029 --> 00:07:52,238
which is actually about 18 miles from my house.

241
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,129
So I got an e-bike and the process

242
00:07:54,129 --> 00:07:56,649
of riding my bike to work on the bike trails

243
00:07:56,649 --> 00:07:58,669
listening to an audio book, getting to learn,

244
00:07:58,670 --> 00:08:00,980
but also getting to be outside and be active

245
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:02,609
is something that I actively look forward to

246
00:08:02,610 --> 00:08:03,600
every single morning.

247
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:06,229
And whenever I get to do it, I'm super excited to get up

248
00:08:06,230 --> 00:08:08,030
get dressed and get out of the door.

249
00:08:08,029 --> 00:08:10,519
And to dwell on this example for a moment,

250
00:08:10,519 --> 00:08:12,479
there's another great thing about this bike ride,

251
00:08:12,480 --> 00:08:14,750
which is that it's an example of what I call

252
00:08:14,750 --> 00:08:16,020
useful movement.

253
00:08:16,019 --> 00:08:17,809
In other words, I have a purpose

254
00:08:17,810 --> 00:08:20,800
for getting outside and getting nearly an hour of exercise.

255
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,650
And this is something I've been thinking about a lot lately

256
00:08:22,649 --> 00:08:25,459
because the way in which we design our urban environments

257
00:08:25,459 --> 00:08:29,127
especially suburban environments where I live right now

258
00:08:29,127 --> 00:08:31,469
kind of forces people in many cases

259
00:08:31,470 --> 00:08:33,970
to exercise in ways that are arbitrary.

260
00:08:33,970 --> 00:08:35,847
They have to convince themselves to go to the gym.

261
00:08:35,847 --> 00:08:38,388
They only real reason for moving

262
00:08:38,389 --> 00:08:40,969
in an intense or lengthy wage day

263
00:08:40,970 --> 00:08:42,869
is guilt or this feeling

264
00:08:42,870 --> 00:08:45,019
that you have to stay physically active.

265
00:08:45,019 --> 00:08:45,929
But when you design your life

266
00:08:45,929 --> 00:08:49,609
in a way where you have a reason to go somewhere actively

267
